import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
"63": {
"1": "<p>Who is this coming from Edom, from Bozrah, with his garments stained crimson? Who is this, robed in splendor, striding forward in the greatness of his strength? It is I, proclaiming victory, mighty to save. The divine warrior returning from battle with garments stained in blood — one of the OT's most arresting images. Revelation 19:13 applies it directly to the returning Christ: <em>he is clothed in a robe dipped in blood, and the name by which he is called is The Word of God.</em> Revelation 19:11: <em>I saw heaven opened, and behold, a white horse! The one sitting on it is called Faithful and True, and in righteousness he judges and makes war.</em> The crimson garments of Isaiah 63 belong to the same figure as the bloodstained robe of Revelation 19 — Christ returning as conquering judge.</p>",
"2": "<p>Why is your apparel red, and your garments like those of one who treads in the wine press? The question about the bloodstained garments that receives the winepress answer in verse 3. Revelation 14:19-20: <em>the angel swung his sickle across the earth and gathered the grape harvest of the earth and threw it into the great winepress of the wrath of God.</em> Revelation 19:15: the returning Christ <em>will tread the winepress of the fury of the wrath of God the Almighty.</em> The winepress of divine judgment that Isaiah 63 describes is the instrument of Christ's eschatological justice — the same warrior who absorbed divine wrath at the cross executes divine justice at the parousia.</p>",
"3": "<p>I have trodden the winepress alone, and from the peoples no one was with me; I trod them in my anger and trampled them in my wrath; their lifeblood spattered on my garments, and stained all my apparel. The warrior trodding the winepress alone — <em>no one was with me.</em> This solitude resonates powerfully with Gethsemane and Golgotha: <em>all the disciples left him and fled</em> (Matt 26:56). Jesus drank the cup of wrath alone: <em>Is it not the cup the Father has given me to drink?</em> (John 18:11). The solitary treading is the aloneness of the cross in its first form; in its eschatological reversal, the same warrior alone executes the judgment no human power can accomplish (2 Thess 1:7-9).</p>",
"4": "<p>For the day of vengeance was in my heart, and my year of redemption has come. The day of vengeance and the year of redemption held together — divine justice and divine mercy as simultaneous realities. This is the logic of the atonement: Romans 3:25-26 — God presented Christ as a propitiation <em>to show his righteousness at the present time, so that he might be just and the justifier of the one who has faith in Jesus.</em> Isaiah 61:2, which Jesus reads in Luke 4:18-19, stops at <em>the year of the LORD's favor</em> — omitting the <em>day of vengeance</em> — reserving that element for the second coming. The first coming is the year of redemption; the second is the day of vengeance. Both are in the divine heart simultaneously.</p>",
"5": "<p>I looked, but there was no one to help; I was appalled, but there was no one to uphold; so my own arm brought me salvation, and my wrath upheld me. No helper — so YHWH's own arm saves. This is the parallel of Isaiah 59:16: <em>there was no man... then his own arm brought him salvation.</em> Hebrews 1:3: the Son upholds <em>the universe by the word of his power.</em> 1 Timothy 2:5: <em>there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus.</em> When no human arm could accomplish what was required, the divine arm itself became flesh — the incarnation as YHWH's response to the absence of any human redeemer. The arm that was not shortened (Isa 59:1) is the arm that brings salvation alone.</p>",
"6": "<p>I trampled down the peoples in my anger; I made them drunk in my wrath, and I poured out their lifeblood on the earth. The divine execution of eschatological judgment on the nations. Revelation 14:20: the blood from the winepress flows <em>as high as a horse's bridle, for 1,600 stadia.</em> 2 Thessalonians 1:7-9: the Lord Jesus will be revealed from heaven in flaming fire, <em>inflicting vengeance on those who do not know God and on those who do not obey the gospel of our Lord Jesus.</em> The judgment of Isaiah 63:6 is the judgment of the returning Christ — the one who absorbed the cup of wrath at the cross now administers it to those who refused the cup of salvation.</p>",
"7": "<p>I will recount the steadfast love of the LORD, the praises of the LORD, according to all that the LORD has granted us, and the great goodness to the house of Israel that he has granted them according to his compassion, according to the abundance of his steadfast love. The pivot from judgment (vv1-6) to recollection of YHWH's hesed. Titus 3:4-5: <em>when the goodness and loving kindness of God our Savior appeared, he saved us, not because of works done by us in righteousness, but according to his own mercy.</em> 2 Corinthians 1:3: <em>the Father of mercies and God of all comfort.</em> The steadfast love recounted in Isaiah 63:7 finds its supreme expression in John 3:16: the love that gave the only Son is the fullness of the hesed the chapter recalls.</p>",
"8": "<p>For he said, Surely they are my people, children who will not deal falsely. And he became their Savior. The covenant declaration — <em>my people</em> — followed immediately by the Savior-title. Matthew 1:21: <em>you shall call his name Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins.</em> Hebrews 2:13 cites Isaiah 8:18 of Christ: <em>Behold, I and the children God has given me</em> — identifying the covenant community as the children the Son of God calls his own. 1 Peter 2:10: <em>once you were not a people, but now you are God's people.</em> The Savior-declaration of Isaiah 63:8 is the naming-commission given to Joseph in Matthew 1: Jesus is the Savior who fulfills what YHWH declared in Isaiah 63.</p>",
"9": "<p>In all their affliction he was afflicted, and the angel of his presence saved them; in his love and in his pity he redeemed them; he lifted them up and carried them all the days of old. <em>In all their affliction he was afflicted</em> — the divine solidarity with suffering. Hebrews 4:15: <em>we do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses, but one who in every respect has been tempted as we are, yet without sin.</em> Matthew 25:40: <em>as you did it to one of the least of these my brothers, you did it to me.</em> The incarnation is YHWH's affliction-solidarity taken to its ultimate form: the divine suffering-with is enacted when the eternal Son bears our griefs and carries our sorrows (Isa 53:4) — not from a distance but from within human experience.</p>",
"10": "<p>But they rebelled and grieved his Holy Spirit; therefore he turned to be their enemy, and himself fought against them. <em>Grieving the Holy Spirit</em> — the only explicit OT occurrence of this concept. Ephesians 4:30: <em>do not grieve the Holy Spirit of God, by whom you were sealed for the day of redemption.</em> Paul's prohibition is rooted in Isaiah 63:10's history: the Spirit who can be grieved is the same Spirit who seals new covenant believers. The rebellion-that-grieves is not an abstract theological category but a concrete covenant pattern — and its consequence (YHWH becoming their enemy) is the pattern that the cross reverses: Romans 5:10 — <em>while we were enemies we were reconciled to God by the death of his Son.</em></p>",
"11": "<p>Then he remembered the days of old, of Moses and his people. Where is he who brought them up out of the sea with the shepherds of his flock? Where is he who put in the midst of them his Holy Spirit. The appeal to Exodus memory — the Spirit who was present in the cloud-pillar and through the wilderness. 1 Corinthians 10:1-4: the Israelites all passed through the sea, all ate spiritual food, all drank from the spiritual Rock — <em>and the Rock was Christ.</em> The Spirit in the midst of them (v11) is the Spirit that Pentecost pours out in new covenant fullness — the same divine Presence who accompanied the first exodus now accompanying the new-exodus community gathered around the risen Christ.</p>",
"12": "<p>Who caused his glorious arm to go at the right hand of Moses, who divided the waters before them to make for himself an everlasting name. The glorious arm at Moses's right that split the sea — the arm of YHWH in Exodus action. Acts 2:33: <em>being therefore exalted at the right hand of God, and having received from the Father the promise of the Holy Spirit, he has poured out this that you yourselves are seeing and hearing.</em> Christ at the Father's right hand exercises the same arm-authority that divided the sea. Philippians 2:9: <em>God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name</em> — the everlasting name made at the Exodus is the name above all names given to the one who bore the cross.</p>",
"13": "<p>Who led them through the depths? Like a horse in the desert, they did not stumble. The safe passage through the depths without stumbling. 1 Corinthians 10:5-10: despite passing through the sea and eating spiritual food (Christ), many of Israel stumbled — as a warning to the church. Jude 24: Christ <em>is able to keep you from stumbling and to present you blameless before the presence of his glory with great joy.</em> The one who led Israel through the depths without stumbling is the one who promises: <em>no one will snatch them out of my hand</em> (John 10:28). The ability to lead through the depths without stumbling is the pastoral power of the Good Shepherd who goes before his flock.</p>",
"14": "<p>Like livestock that go down into the valley, the Spirit of the LORD gave them rest. So you led your people, to make for yourself a glorious name. The Spirit-given rest — the Exodus settlement as a type of the eschatological Sabbath-rest. Hebrews 4:8-11: if Joshua had given them rest, God would not have spoken of another day — <em>there remains a Sabbath rest for the people of God.</em> Matthew 11:28-29: <em>come to me, all who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest... for I am gentle and lowly in heart, and you will find rest for your souls.</em> The Spirit who gave rest in the valley-settlement is the Spirit that Christ sends (John 14:16-17) to give the deeper rest that Joshua's conquest could not provide.</p>",
"15": "<p>Look down from heaven and see, from your holy and beautiful habitation. Where are your zeal and your might? The stirring of your inner parts and your compassion are held back from me. The prayer for YHWH to look down from his holy habitation and act from compassion. John 3:16-17: <em>God so loved the world that he gave his only Son... for God did not send his Son into the world to condemn the world, but in order that the world might be saved through him.</em> The prayer of Isaiah 63:15 is answered beyond what the prayer could imagine: YHWH does not merely look down from his holy habitation — he enters human history in the person of the Son. The compassion that appeared withheld is poured out at the incarnation and cross.</p>",
"16": "<p>For you are our Father, though Abraham does not know us and Israel does not acknowledge us; you, O LORD, are our Father, our Redeemer from of old is your name. The covenantal Abba-cry — <em>you are our Father</em>. Romans 8:15-16: <em>you have received the Spirit of adoption as sons, by whom we cry, Abba! Father! The Spirit himself bears witness with our spirit that we are children of God.</em> Galatians 4:6: <em>because you are sons, God has sent the Spirit of his Son into our hearts, crying, Abba! Father!</em> The cry of Isaiah 63:16 is the cry the Spirit enables believers to make through union with the Son — who is himself the eternal Son who in Gethsemane prays <em>Abba, Father, all things are possible for you</em> (Mark 14:36). Our Abba-cry is a participation in his.</p>",
"17": "<p>O LORD, why do you make us wander from your ways and harden our heart, so that we fear you not? Return for the sake of your servants, the tribes of your heritage. The lament over hardening — YHWH's mysterious judicial action. Romans 11:25: <em>a partial hardening has come upon Israel, until the fullness of the Gentiles has come in.</em> Romans 9:18: God hardens whom he wills — but always in service of ultimate mercy (Rom 11:32: <em>he has consigned all to disobedience, that he may have mercy on all</em>). The hardening that Isaiah 63:17 laments is the same partial hardening whose resolution Paul sees in the Redeemer coming from Zion (Rom 11:26, citing Isa 59:20). The return for the sake of YHWH's servants is the return of Christ.</p>",
"18": "<p>Your holy people held possession for a little while; our adversaries have trampled down your sanctuary. The sanctuary trampled by enemies — the desecration of the holy place. Mark 13:14: Jesus predicts the <em>abomination of desolation</em> in the holy place. Luke 21:20-24: armies surrounding Jerusalem, Gentiles trampling it <em>until the times of the Gentiles are fulfilled.</em> The 70 CE destruction of the temple is the historical fulfillment — and Jesus's prediction of it links Isaiah 63:18 to the eschatological timetable: the trampling of the sanctuary ends when the times of the Gentiles are complete and the Deliverer comes from Zion (Rom 11:26).</p>",
"19": "<p>We have become like those over whom you have never ruled, like those who are not called by your name. The lament of lost identity — <em>not called by your name.</em> 1 Peter 2:10: <em>once you were not a people, but now you are God's people; once you had not received mercy, but now you have received mercy.</em> In Christ, every believer is restored to the status of those-called-by-his-name. Revelation 22:4: <em>they will see his face, and his name will be on their foreheads.</em> Revelation 3:12: Christ writes on the overcomer <em>the name of my God and the name of the city of my God... and my own new name.</em> The lost name of Isaiah 63:19 is restored and surpassed in Christ — those who were not his people become the ones who bear the name of the Son himself.</p>"
}
}

data = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'isaiah')
merge_comm(data, NEW)
save_comm('mkt-christ', 'isaiah', data)
